'''Syncretism''' or the '''Mixed School''' in [[Chinese philosophy]] is an eclectic [[Hundred Schools of Thought|school of thought]] that combined elements of [[Confucianism]], [[Taoism]], [[Mohism]], and [[Legalism (Chinese philosophy)|Legalism]]. The Syncretist texts include the ''[[Huainanzi]]'', ''[[Lüshi Chunqiu]]'', and the ''[[Shizi (book)|Shizi]]''.<ref name="Shizi">{{cite book|author=Jiao Shi|author2=Paul Fischer|title=Shizi: China's First Syncretist|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KXkVURzR4kgC|date=1 June 2012|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=978-0-231-50417-1|page=11}}</ref> The (c. 330 BCE) ''Shizi'' is the earliest of the Syncretist texts.
